Thanks for all your insight on my last post. It was so interesting reading all your thought and experiences with Instagram tourism around the world. Certainly something we should always be thinking of.

Burano Island üåà
.

I have never seen the 'Instagram effect' on a destination as much as I saw in Burano. This tiny island of rainbow painted houses is indeed incredibly photogenic, but it's also a place that people call home. Early in the morning when I arrived, it was a sanctuary of calm. Women knitted outside their houses, rung out their laundry and men fixed their boats on the canals which replace roads. A few hours later, masses of tourists arrived on ferries, and the locals retreated inside and locked their shutters closed, while daytrippers posed with their laundry lines and patio displays for the perfect shot. .

I am too a tourist and an Instagrammer. I shoot often on the streets and local people appear in a great portion of my photographs. The place left me with a big dilemma in my mind, one I'm still trying to figure out. Tourism can do wonders for communities, but at the extreme - it can also shatter them and I fear Burano may become the next victim. What are your thoughts on this? Have you found similar places around the world?

My last stop in Italy was Venice. Despite the glorious beauty of it all, I was disappointed by the lack of soul in the city. But I can't deny that it was a pretty stunning place to photograph. The gondola drivers were some of my favourites to shoot, each with their own personality and style. Have you ever been to Venice? Would love to hear what others thought of it!

Puglia is a place everyone is talking about at the moment. I only spent a few days in the Southern Italian region, but definitely felt that Puglia feeling. The cities are white washed, clean and sea fronted. The people are friendly and as with everywhere in Italy, the food is delicious. This was taken in Polignano a Mare, a small town built on the edges of cliffs.
Neapolitan scenes üáÆüáπ

An artist takes a smoking break outside his studio in Matera, Italy üáÆüáπ

Matera is one of the oldest continuously inhabited places in the world. People have lived in cave houses in this valley for 9000 years. In the 1960's, it was known as the shame of Italy - full of poverty, disease and families living in the cave structures alongside their animals. It was cleared by the government and the residents moved into modern housing nearby. The ancient city was empty and left for ruin. But in the last few decades, people have started to return, and it's now a hub of arts, culture and trendy hotels and restaurants.

A game of cards in Piazza Dante, Naples, Italy.
.
The sun was setting when I took this photo and the square was a picture of local life. Women rumbled through baskets of cheap books at a market stall, young boys kicked a football between the long, elegant shadows of the square and men gathered around benches drinking beers and playing cards. Shortly after I headed to Sorbillo and had the best pizza of my life üáÆüáπ #italy

Taking you to the sunny South of Italy and the vibrant city of Naples. I LOVED this place. The city has this electric vibe running through the streets, reminding me more of an Asian metropolis than anywhere else I'd visited in Europe. Plus, the food is unreal üçï #italy üáÆüáπ

I've posted another shot from this morning before, but this place is too magical not to show a different perspective. These root bridges connect the villages of the East Khasi Hills, and survive much better than modern iron bridges when the state experiences heavy rainfall during monsoon. They are created by the Khasi tribes people, who use human power together with the magic of the native rubber trees to weave these roots into strong, stable structures.
.

Meghalaya is one of the wettest places on earth, and the jungle clad state is home to some incredible root bridges. What really blew me away about this place was the Khasi tribal people who call it home. This woman was preparing beetlenut outside her home. #india #lodestarsanthology

node.text: On one of the hottest days of the year, I take you back to my coldest (in fact, the coldest of my life). This was as we set off from High Camp and headed over the Thorong La Pass at 5416m. The winds were blisteringly cold, I couldn't feel my face and to be honest, at the time I was far too cold to appreciate this moment. And while I'll always take a scorching hot summers day over snow and ice, I'll always make an exception for these mountains ‚ù§Ô∏è

node.text:
In the Thar Desert, Rajasthan, India.
.
I'm really pleased to be judging this week's @passionpassport hashtag challenge, #PPTravelEncounters. We want you to post photos and stories of the most memorable encounters you have had on your travels. I can't wait to see your entries! Here's one of mine.
.
We arrived at a semi-abandoned village in the Thar Desert, not far from the Pakistan border. We were supposed to take camels from this point, go go deeper into the dunes. But when we arrived there was no camels, and our guides all went to find some while we sat with a group of women and children from the village. This woman was one of them, and as the hours went by she braided my hair, I took her portrait and we had mismatched conversations in broken English over steaming pots of tea. When we finally found some camels, she wished me fairwell by writing her name on my arm in henna. It remained there for a few weeks after, and many other locals I met commented that her name meant 'Love'. üáÆüá≥

Luxor Temple, Egypt.
.
A country which I loved so much. From waking up with the call to prayer, to the friendliest locals, the most delicious food, camel markets and having temples like this all to myself. I travelled solo to Egypt a few years ago, and found despite the rich cultural heritage of the country, it was almost empty of travellers. üá™üá¨

Marrakesh, Morocco üá≤üá¶
.
A busker on the side of a street in Marrakesh's winding red Medina. I often get asked how I take portraits of people, and I want to share a very easy tip to get you started. While it might be initially difficult to go up to a stranger and ask to photograph them, street buskers and performers expect it. Give them your spare change and snap a few shots of them üì∏

Bhaktapur, Nepal, March 2018.
.

Another one to add to my 'people reading papers in South Asia' series which I'm getting really into üòÇüòÇ. Scroll back to see the Kolkata set I posted a few weeks ago for the rest. üì∞
.
Hope everyone had a lovely weekend! What did you get up to?

The Tawang Valley, Arunachal Pradesh, India. .

I often get asked how I take the photographs I do. I particularly want to share some back stories of my portraits, as this seems to intrigue people the most, but today I'm going to talk about light, perhaps the most important component of photography. .

This shot was taken at sunrise. I'd been up since 4:30am shooting early morning prayers in the Tawang Monastery. As the sun spilled over the mountains, light rays shone down on the valleys below as the fog rose from the ground after a chilly night. .

It only happened for a few minutes, but part of being a photographer is knowing where to be at the right time, and the best photographs always happen when light and timing come together in a perfect, magic moment ‚ú®.

A portrait of Tenzin, a Buddhist nun at the Brahma Dung Chung Monastery in Tawang, Arunachal Pradesh, India. .

My love for India is probably very clear to anyone who has been following me for a while. I first travelled to India 4 years ago to learn more about Tibetan Buddhism. I spent 10 days at a retreat in Both Gaya and then several weeks volunteering in Dharamsala, where the Dalai Lama calls home. I've always felt a strong connection to Tibetan Buddhism, and whenever I go to an area where it is the main religion, I feel very at peace. .

Tawang, which I visited on my most recent trip is one such place. A valley backed by dawn lit mountains, where the humming of red robbed monks and nuns seems to spill through the air.

Darjeeling, India. Boxing Day 2017.

You may have noticed I've been a little quiet on here for the past month. While I'm always grateful for this app and the opportunities it has brought me, I've become more and more frustrated with the lack of originality I see on here, and with the algorithm (so many people have talked about this, I know!) So I needed to step back and disengage for a while. .

I've still been spending lots of time behind a camera, and I've got some exciting magazine features coming out in the summer. I've also been spending lots of time getting great content on @roam.magazine - do go check out the site if you haven't already! In the meantime, I thought I'd get back to posting some of my images from the road, and I'd like to spend more time engaging with you guys too. .

So let me know, what would you like to see more of from me? Blogs? Showing more of my photographer life on my stories? Q&A's, or just generally getting to know me better? Or should I just stick to photography? Let me know! ‚úåÔ∏è

Glowing morning sun in the backstreets of Nepal. Thank you for following my journey around this amazing country! I've had so many lovely comments and messages on my Nepal photos, and it's very nice to hear that many of you are inspired to visit!üá≥üáµ #nepal

When I visited Nepal after the earthquake, Boudha was a tower of scaffolding. But now it's restored to its glory - with Buddha eyes and prayer flags framing this special area in the Kathmandu Valley üá≥üáµ #nepal

Red, in the Hindu world, is taken to be the colour of life, of the glowing sun and of passion. This is a portrait of a beautiful market stall seller I met while wandering Bhaktapur early in the morning. Like many Nepali women, she wore the striking colour with so miuch beauty and grace. üá≥üáµ #nepal

There are many symbols of Nepal which you'll see time and time again when you travel through the county - Buddha eyes, prayer flags, the famous flag üá≥üáµ. Another is the Dhaka Topi, a hat worn by local men and a symbol of Nepali pride. The hat even has its own day - the International Day of the Nepali Topi, celebrated on January 1st every year. #ROAMtravels #nepal
Store fronts of Kathmandu's Asan Role area üá≥üáµ #nepal
Potters Square, Bhaktapur. A city full of arts and culture, with someone creating something beautiful (or tasty!) on every corner. #nepal üá≥üáµ

From the mountains to the ancient cities... I took this portrait of a potter in Bhaktapur, one of my favourite spots in the Kathmandu Valley. Looking forward to showing you more of the rest of Nepal! üá≥üáµ #nepal
Towards mountains ‚ú®üá≥üáµ #nepal

Prayer Wheels on the trail. Some old and intricately painted, and some using very innovative recycling ideas. All are spun by passing locals and trekkers, sending prayers into the unpredictable mountains which surrounded us. #nepal üá≥üáµ

The white painted streets of Marpha, a village in Mustang, Nepal. Marpha was one of my favourite villages on the trail, it's narrow streets reminded me of Moroccan Medina's. The village was surrounded by apple orchards, filled with Tibetan handicraft shops and in the centre is an old and very welcoming Nyingma Monastery. üçéüá≥üáµ #nepal
Another of the sweet faces I found around Manang #nepal üá≥üáµ
Horses on the trail to the Manang Valley üêé #nepal üá≥üáµ

My sister and my mountains ‚ô•Ô∏è. If you ever do the circuit trek, make sure you do the side trek to the Braga Ice Lake. While the lake was frozen and covered in snow when we got there, the panoramic views of the Annapurnas on the way up made it so worthwhile #nepal üá≥üáµ
A young face in Manang, a beautiful Tibetan village on the trail #nepal üá≥üáµ

An essential part of the Annapurna Trail - momos. After a long day of hiking, we all looked forward to the food every evening in the trails tea houses. We would feast on Dal Bhat, potato curries, apple pies and these little bundles of joy #nepal üá≥üáµ
Road to Annapurna II #nepal üá≥üáµ
A local face in Manang, on out acclimatization day while trekking the Annapurna Circuit #nepal üá≥üáµ
The streets of Marpha, one of my favourite villages on the Annapurna Trail üá≥üáµ #nepal

Anyone who has hiked the Annapurna Circuit will know that the day of the Thorong La Pass is a killer. We battler thick snow, blustering ice winds and temperatures of -25¬∞C to get over the pass which sits at 5416m. It was hell for the most part, although we got the greatest feeling of joy when we finally saw those flags and reached the top.

As we descended down the other side, the winds stopped, the sun came out and we got these wide open views over the valley to Muktinath. Can you spot the tiny hiker in this photo? üö∂#nepal
A young woman and her child in Muktinath, a spiritual town on the Annapurna Circuit Trek in Nepal. #ROAMtravels #nepal üá≥üáµ‚ô•Ô∏è

The first few months of the year have been quite a blur of planes and colours, golden beaches, exotic festivals and glowing mountains. From India, I returned to the UK for a few weeks and then flew out to Kathmandu.

Khasi culture is matrilineal, meaning the family name and ancestral property is passed down the female line of the family rather than the male as is still seen in most societies around the world. The birth of a girl is celebrated. 
Travelling through this region, you see the independence, power and status women have - something which feels very distinct from the rest of India. #incredibleindia #meghalaya üáÆüá≥

From Assam I travelled south to Meghalaya state and the East Khasi Hills. Between green rolling hills I found lush jungles, villages lost in another time and one of the most unique and unexpected cultures I have come across anywhere on my travels around India - the Khasi tribes.

Of course, the main reason I traveled to this region is for the root bridges, which are created from the roots of the rubber trees which grow in the area. This is one of the most spectacular - the double decker root bridge of Nongriat #incredibleindia üáÆüá≥üå≤

For a while now I've been considering starting a project celebrating travel stories, creativity and off the beaten track guides to some of my favourite places in the world. So I'm really happy to introduce @roam.magazine to you! 
It's going to be a place to put my own stories and adventures, and hopefully a place for YOU to share your travel stories too. We are currently on the hunt for any creative travellers who are interested in contributing or being interviewed. Email hello@roam-magazine.co if that might be you! I went on a camel safari but our guide realised he didn't have enough camels and left us in a remote desert village for a few hours. Here, I met this women, who quickly become a little obsessed with me and my blondness. She braided my hair, painted my toenails barbie pink and henna tattooed her name on my arm. In the end the guide translated that she wanted me to come and live with her in the village for a while but alas, the dunes were calling. 
I love taking portraits of people, but in the end it's always the memories and laughter behind them that make the shot. üáÆüá≥

I heard a rumour about a baba who lives deep in the desert mountains around Pushkar and eats only potatoes. They call him 'Aloo Baba'. I took a motorbike out to his temple, where he lives among around 30 wild peacocks and has planted 300 trees in the surrounding hillside.

'There are some moments in life that are like pivots around which your existence turns- small intuitive flashes, when you know you have done something correct for a change, when you think you are on the right track. I watched a pale dawn streak the cliffs with Day-glo, and realised this was one of them. It was a moment of pure, uncomplicated confidence- that lasted about ten seconds'

It's wonderful to be surrounded by mountains, cool clean air, tea shops and rice paddies. Looking forward to a weekend of switching off and writing. See you on the other side ‚úå
Mornings at Inle Lake ‚öì

My heart is aching hearing about the tragedies and loss of life sweeping Nepal. I feel so bonded to that country, to the people and the mountains. I experienced so much kindness from the Nepali people, who are generous, kind and peaceful in nature. I hope at a time like this many people can send love, light and whatever money they can to help get the country back on its feet. ‚ù§

#PrayforNepal

One of my favourite shots of Al Azhar Park and Cairo city at sunset. I've watched the sunset over a fair few city skylines around the globe, but this one was really something else. 
Will be posting some Egypt photos this week to go with my latest blog post on solo travel in the country.
